an elements in spirit names in Dongbaism and Dabaism -- tChapter 12 The appropriation of animal names as personal names in Ibibio and Tiv onomastic traditions in Nigeria: An ethnopragmatic study -- tChapter 13 A structural study of Basà death prevention names -- tSection Four: Cultural implications in anthroponym typology -- tChapter 14 Typology and motivations for Azerbaijani personal names -- tChapter 15 The grammar of personal names in Saaroa -- tChapter 16 Personal names and naming in Tongan language and culture -- tChapter 17 A descriptive account of the modern Mazahuan onomastic system -- tChapter 18 Gender intimations in the morphology of some Ndebele personal names -- tNotes on contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book fills a gap in the literature as it uniquely approaches onomastics from the perspective of both anthropology and linguistics. It addresses names and cultures from 16 countries and five continents, thus offering readers an opportunity to comprehend and compare names and naming practices across cultures. The chapters presented in this book explore the cultural significance of personal names, naming ceremonies, conventions and practices. They illustrate how these names and practices perform certain culture-specific functions, such as religion, identity and social activity. Some chapters address the socio-political significance of personal names and their expression of self and otherness. The book also links the linguistic structure of personal names to culture by looking at their morphology, syntax and semantics. It is divided into four sections: Section 1 demonstrates how personal names perform human culture, Section 2 focuses on how personal names index socio-political transitioning, Section 3 demonstrates religious values in personal names and naming, and Section 4 links linguistic structure and analysis of personal names to culture and heritage.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAnthropologie. 4aKultur. 4aOnomastik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aCulture.  aPerform.  aPersonal Names.1 aBaranauskiene, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDammel, Antje, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabibli, Reyhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKus, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandman, Shlomit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLungisani Chigidi, Willie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManda Imoh, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeinerzag, Angella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMensah, Eyo O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMickiene, Ilona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNdlovu, Sambulo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNdlovu, Sambulo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPan, Chia-Jung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrollino, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaharijaona, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReyes Contreras, Miguel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinger, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSipavicius Seide, Márcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSylvester Kahyana, Danson, econtributor.4ctb4htt